explanation:
OS_OBJECT_TABLE_GET: Macro used to obtain `impl` — its expansion may perform checks or additional operations; needed to determine whether the lookup (and any side effects) can be removed without changing behaviour.

OS_impl_mutex_table: The underlying table used by the macro — required to know whether the lookup or any data reads/writes matter to program state (i.e. whether removing the lookup is observable).

OS_object_token_t: The token type passed into the function; required to know whether passing the token or extracting an index has side effects (e.g. if it embeds special semantics) and thus whether the function call can be eliminated.

OS_impl_mutex_internal_record_t: Definition of the structure returned by the table lookup, and specifically the type/layout of `id` — needed to know if accessing `impl->id` is meaningful and whether removing code that touches it would affect behaviour.

OS_ObjectIndexFromToken: Call graph shows this is called by the table-get path; its semantics (side effects, error handling) are needed to assess whether the lookup/call is dead.

pthread_mutex_destroy: The function invoked — required because it has side effects on the underlying mutex object and can fail; must be inspected to determine if its invocation is required for correct program behaviour (destroying the mutex is an observable effect).

pthread_mutex_t: Type of the `id` field — to confirm that `impl->id` is a mutex and that calling pthread_mutex_destroy on it has the usual POSIX semantics (i.e. non-trivial observable effect).

OS_SEM_FAILURE and OS_SUCCESS: Return-code macros/constants used by the function — needed to determine how callers react to the return values and whether altering or removing these return-value-producing operations would affect program behaviour.

OS_MutSemDelete: The immediate caller — required to check whether this impl function is actually invoked in normal operation and whether its return value or side effects are used (to decide if the function body is removable).

OS_CleanUpObject: A higher-level caller of OS_MutSemDelete (per call graph) — included to trace reachability and determine whether the target function (or parts of it) are ever invoked in active code paths; necessary to conclude whether the code is dead.

(These symbols collectively allow analysis of: whether the lookup and pthread_mutex_destroy call have observable side effects, whether return values propagate to code that relies on them, and whether the function is reachable — all needed to decide if any operations in the function are dead code under MISRA.)
